==ِArabic name transliteration==
I'm pretty sure the Arabic name is actually ({{lang-ar|عضد الدولة}}) which is transliterated as 'Adod al-Dawla, and means the "arm of the state" which could be construed as the "instrument of the state" as cited in the text. The transliteration you cite though (ʿUddat al-Dawla) corresponds to ({{lang-ar|عدة الدولة}}) which ''literally'' means the ''instrument'' of the state, but is plainly wrong as far as Arabic sources are concerned. I think there might be some confusion here! [[User:Zozo2kx|Yazan]] ([[User talk:Zozo2kx|talk]]) 14:56, 15 November 2012 (UTC)

:What do you mean by "plainly wrong as far as Arabic sources are concerned"? Do you have Arabic sources that have the former name? Because Canard is pretty clear: "persuaded the caliph to grant the ''laqab'' of ʿUddat al-Dawla". Cheers, [[User:Cplakidas|Constantine]]  [[User talk:Cplakidas| ✍ ]] 15:06, 15 November 2012 (UTC)
::(ec)Actually scratch that; Arabic sources seem to be just as confused. The [http://books.google.co.jp/books?id=3kZAAQAAIAAJ&q=%22%D8%B9%D8%AF%D8%A9+%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84%D8%A9%22+%22%D8%A3%D8%A8%D9%88+%D8%AA%D8%BA%D9%84%D8%A8%22&dq=%22%D8%B9%D8%AF%D8%A9+%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%84%D8%A9%22+%22%D8%A3%D8%A8%D9%88+%D8%AA%D8%BA%D9%84%D8%A8%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bQSlUJ6qIoikmQWTroHIDA&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA only] reliable source I could find mentions him as "Uddat al-Dawla", so I'll change it to that. [[User:Zozo2kx|Yazan]] ([[User talk:Zozo2kx|talk]]) 15:07, 15 November 2012 (UTC)
